<div class="twelve_section_2" >
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				Well, a “harrow” is a type of rake that was used in the past to break up the clods of dirt left in the field after plowing. To harrow literally means to cause distress to something, so in that sense it would seem that to be harrowed by something would be a negative experience. But Tarkovsky is using it in a positive sense. To me, it seems an interesting concept, because it evokes the idea of something that is not necessarily “enjoyable” in the traditional sense of being fun, but that is necessary and has a positive outcome or influence. This might not be the typical experience we’re looking for when going to the movies as a leisure activity, but it is, nevertheless, another thing that movies can do.
			</p>
			<p>
				As you watch <em>Code Unknown</em> this week, I want you to pay attention to three different aspects of the film. 
			</p>
			<h3>STRUCTURAL</h3>
			<p>
				We’ve laid out above some of the ways that ensemble films deviate structurally from other films. <em>Code Unknown</em> shares some of those deviations, but it also deviates further from typical ensemble films. Instead of following different threads and gradually seeing them link up in some way as they build toward conflict and resolution, this film starts with a moment of conflict between multiple parties, then follows those individual parties as they go their separate ways, watching the various strands of the story move apart and unravel.
			</p>
			<p>
				As you watch the film, think about how the various characters are treated. Is there a “main” character? How many or what kinds of traits do the characters have? How do those traits motivate the cause-and-effect chain? How many chains are there? Is there any change or development in the characters over the course of the film?
			</p>
			<h3>THEMATIC</h3>
			<p>
				We’ve raised the question over the semester of what we might say that a film’s priorities are: whether or not the film is primarily interested in the plot, the characters or the themes. I’ll just come right out and say that in this film the events of the plot and the characterizations are going to be subservient to the themes and ideas that the film is interested in exploring. Bring to bear your experience from previous weeks in examining <em>Gummo</em> to find thematic similarities throughout the various scenes of that film. What ideas or themes are repeated in the different threads of storyline that Haneke presents to us? What common ground can you find between the various characters who have very tenuous plot-level connections with each other (Here’s a hint: how many different languages are spoken in this film)? 
			</p>
			<h3>TECHNICAL</h3>
			<p>
				The style of this film is also a little bit different from a “normal” technical approach to storytelling. I don’t want to overdetermine your response by going into too much detail beforehand, but as you watch think about: what is it that’s unusual about the camerawork? The use of editing? The approach to time?	
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
